		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1449508)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1449508">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chazzk" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1203158); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1203158&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203981" alt="ChazzK" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1203158)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chazzk" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1203158); return false;" >ChazzK</a></span> <span class="odate time_1337097365 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 May 2012 15:56</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1449508">
									

<p>In my head, and what seems to be more-or-less the somewhat more common things, goes as follows:</p>
<p>Class A causes a &quot;hard reset.&quot; Anything up to a certain amount of time is wiped more-or-less clean, with the dosage amount figuring in the amount of time wiped out.</p>
<p>Class B partially wipes and leaves the recipient confused and impressionable; this is more like the Neurolizer from the MIB movies/cartoon, the people might vaguely recall something going on, but the cover story overrides it (Dude, I saw this car drive straight through a wall today! Well.. I mean yeah the wall was messed up, but I swear that car looked like it didn't have a scratch on it, still had to get towed away though so I guess it just had a hard chassis).</p>
<p>Class C are the weakest of the bunch, mostly affecting short-term memory loss and the like. These are good when that poor bastard with the mouths in his palms gets out and someone spots him eating a burger at a diner without putting it in his face. They just straight don't remember it because it was some &quot;corner of the eye&quot; thing, not enough to make a huge impression, and they basically figured their eyes played tricks on them.</p>
<p>Of course, all of these affect the brain, and there's always the chance of unexpected side-effects since everyone reacts to medication differently. And overdose is ''never'' a good thing.</p>

							</div>

								
					
