					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/digiwizzard" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(389284); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=389284&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203981" alt="Digiwizzard" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=389284)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/digiwizzard" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(389284); return false;" >Digiwizzard</a></span> <span class="odate time_1337099826 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 May 2012 16:37</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1449553">
									

<p>I had pictured it as being sort of the opposite, with potency increasing in orders of magnitude with each class. Class A being just like you said, maybe with hypnotic suggestion so that the subject represses or at least develops a strong aversion to thinking about the missing gaps in their memory. Class B inducing a hollywood style mindwipe where the subject has a complete loss of episodic memory, and Class C just being a low intensity stroke, with the subject losing motor and language function and likely having difficulty in storing or creating new memories.</p>

							</div>

								
